{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489848"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:32:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:32:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"760"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/760"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.37,0.14,0.16,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"760"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55743"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/760"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"760"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41287"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"93"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2590"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3037"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10892"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16903"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55743"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of colicky abdominal pain, bloating and constipation. She has had several similar episodes over the last three months, all of which resolved spontaneously, but the current episode has persisted. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is slightly distended with some tenderness in the right iliac fossa. On auscultation, she has scattered high-pitched bowel sounds. Investigations reveal a haemoglobin of 109 g/L (115-165), MCV 72 fL (80-96), and C-reactive protein 42 mg/L (\u0026lt;5). An abdominal X-ray shows a distal small bowel obstruction. Intravenous fluids are commenced and she settles with nasogastric tube insertion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastroscopy","Colonoscopy","Capsule endoscopy","Diagnostic laparoscopy","MR enterography"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of recurrent incomplete small bowel obstruction, which in given her young age is likely secondary to Crohn\u0027s disease. The history of recurrent episodes, right iliac fossa tenderness, and laboratory findings of likely iron deficiency anaemia and elevated inflammatory markers are all supportive of this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMR enterography\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation out of the provided options. It provides detailed information about the extent and severity of small bowel involvement without exposing the patient to ionizing radiation. MR enterography can identify complications of Crohn\u0027s disease such as strictures, fistulas, and abscesses. CT enterography is a similar modality which may be useful in this setting, but is less preferred due to it associated radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroscopy\u003C/strong\u003E does not provide information about the small bowel beyond the duodenum and so would not be helpful in this case as the obstruction is in the distal small bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E can visualize the colon and terminal ileum and is useful for diagnosing and assessing Crohn\u0027s disease. However, it is not appropriate in this acute setting - the inability to prepare the bowel may limit views, active inflammation may increase the risk of perforation. It would be more appropriate to perform this as an outpatient procedure together with a gastroscopy to evaluate her Crohn\u0027s disease once the acute episode has resolved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECapsule endoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E can be a helpful in assessing small bowel disease, but is contraindicated in cases of known or suspected small bowel obstruction, as the capsule could become lodged at the site of obstruction, potentially worsening the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic laparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that carries risks such as bleeding, infection, and organ injury. It  can provide direct visualization of the abdominal cavity and is typically indicated when diagnosis is unclear or surgical intervention is required. It is not an appropriate investigation in this setting where Crohn\u0027s disease is suspected and where non-invasive imaging options are available.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Crohn\u0027s disease can present acutely with small bowel obstruction.","MR enterography is the preferred imaging modality for suspected Crohn\u0027s disease in young patients due to its lack of radiation exposure and high soft tissue contrast."],"references":["Gomes CA, Podda M, Veiga SC, Cabral TD, Lima LV, Miron LC, et al. Management of inflammatory bowel diseases in urgent and emergency scenario. Journal of Coloproctology. 2020 Mar;40(1):83-8.","Lamb CA, Kennedy NA, Raine T, Hendy PA, Smith PJ, Limdi JK, et al. British Society of Gastroenterology consensus guidelines on the management of inflammatory bowel disease in adults. Gut. 2019 Sep;68:1-106.","Rami Reddy SR, Cappell MS. A systematic review of the clinical presentation, diagnosis, and treatment of small bowel obstruction. Curr Gastroenterol Rep. 2017 Jun;19(6):28","Ford MM. Crohn\u0027s Disease Obstructions. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2021 Jul;34(4):227-232. doi: 10.1055/s-0041-1729926. Epub 2021 Jul 20. PMID: 34305471; PMCID: PMC8292001."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41287"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"760"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41287"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-17T19:31:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T19:32:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"760"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55743"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":